            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="120"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14337459' href='vote?id=14337459&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14336093'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=highd" class="hnuser">highd</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14337459">12 minutes ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14337459"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="1" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14337459)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">FFT and PCA are totally different. FFT is a fixed linear transform - PCA finds the linear projection to k-space that retains the most variance from the original dataset. If you projected to the top k frequencies you&#x27;d just get a couple of tones, while PCA finds linear combinations of the original signal that are most &quot;descriptive&quot; in a sense.<p>Also human hearing is much closer to a wavelet transform or STFT than FFT.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=14337459&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14336093%2314337459">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
